1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,470
- "The stock market is over,

2
00:00:01,470 --> 00:00:02,400
and you should get out

3
00:00:02,400 --> 00:00:05,160
before Trump triggers a
full-blown recession."

4
00:00:05,160 --> 00:00:07,530
That's what the mainstream
media want you to think.

5
00:00:07,530 --> 00:00:09,300
Headlines are screaming disaster,

6
00:00:09,300 --> 00:00:11,160
social media is in a frenzy,

7
00:00:11,160 --> 00:00:13,807
and everyone is asking the same question,

8
00:00:13,807 --> 00:00:16,080
"Should I sell now before it gets worse?"

9
00:00:16,080 --> 00:00:18,090
But there's more to
this than meets the eye.

10
00:00:18,090 --> 00:00:19,740
If you followed me for a while,

11
00:00:19,740 --> 00:00:21,270
you know I'm a serious investor

12
00:00:21,270 --> 00:00:23,430
who's obsessed with the stock market.

13
00:00:23,430 --> 00:00:25,650
And since so many of you
have started investing

14
00:00:25,650 --> 00:00:27,270
because of my videos,

15
00:00:27,270 --> 00:00:28,740
I feel a responsibility

16
00:00:28,740 --> 00:00:31,260
to give you my honest
take on the situation.

17
00:00:31,260 --> 00:00:32,940
So before you panic,

18
00:00:32,940 --> 00:00:34,200
let's take a step back

19
00:00:34,200 --> 00:00:36,390
and look at the bigger picture together.

20
00:00:36,390 --> 00:00:38,490
Every market crash has a cause,

21
00:00:38,490 --> 00:00:40,560
and this one isn't random.

22
00:00:40,560 --> 00:00:42,927
There are three main triggers behind it.

23
00:00:42,927 --> 00:00:45,720
And all of them tie back to one man,

24
00:00:45,720 --> 00:00:46,710
Donald Trump.

25
00:00:46,710 --> 00:00:49,170
Now, before anyone jumps to conclusions,

26
00:00:49,170 --> 00:00:51,180
this isn't about politics.

27
00:00:51,180 --> 00:00:52,830
I'm not here to take sides.

28
00:00:52,830 --> 00:00:54,720
And as a British investor looking in,

29
00:00:54,720 --> 00:00:57,240
my only concern is how
this impacts investors

30
00:00:57,240 --> 00:00:58,230
like you and me.

31
00:00:58,230 --> 00:01:00,840
So let's break down the
three biggest triggers

32
00:01:00,840 --> 00:01:02,070
behind this crash,

33
00:01:02,070 --> 00:01:03,240
why they matter,

34
00:01:03,240 --> 00:01:06,248
and what you can do to
benefit from all this mayhem.

35
00:01:06,248 --> 00:01:08,310
(keys clacking)
(upbeat music)

36
00:01:08,310 --> 00:01:10,530
Trigger one is Trump's trade war.

37
00:01:10,530 --> 00:01:12,120
Trump has always pitched himself

38
00:01:12,120 --> 00:01:13,890
as the ultimate deal maker.

39
00:01:13,890 --> 00:01:16,440
He's the guy who fights for American jobs

40
00:01:16,440 --> 00:01:18,420
and plays hardball with other countries,

41
00:01:18,420 --> 00:01:19,980
but the trade wars he's fighting

42
00:01:19,980 --> 00:01:21,870
could increase your weekly shopping bill

43
00:01:21,870 --> 00:01:23,130
and cause a recession.

44
00:01:23,130 --> 00:01:25,050
The last time the US tried this,

45
00:01:25,050 --> 00:01:27,180
it helped trigger the Great Depression,

46
00:01:27,180 --> 00:01:29,730
wiping out jobs and wrecking the economy.

47
00:01:29,730 --> 00:01:32,340
Now, history might be repeating itself.

48
00:01:32,340 --> 00:01:34,110
Stocks are already crashing,

49
00:01:34,110 --> 00:01:35,550
prices are rising,

50
00:01:35,550 --> 00:01:37,050
and if this spirals,

51
00:01:37,050 --> 00:01:38,790
it won't just hurt Wall Street,

52
00:01:38,790 --> 00:01:40,980
it'll hit you where it matters most,

53
00:01:40,980 --> 00:01:42,060
your bank account.

54
00:01:42,060 --> 00:01:44,220
Let me take you back to 1930,

55
00:01:44,220 --> 00:01:45,900
when I was just a boy,

56
00:01:45,900 --> 00:01:48,960
the US government decided
to slap massive taxes

57
00:01:48,960 --> 00:01:51,090
called tariffs on imported goods

58
00:01:51,090 --> 00:01:52,800
to protect American businesses

59
00:01:52,800 --> 00:01:54,150
from foreign competition.

60
00:01:54,150 --> 00:01:56,580
It was called the Smoot-Hawley Tariff Act,

61
00:01:56,580 --> 00:01:57,750
and it turned out to be

62
00:01:57,750 --> 00:02:00,630
one of the worst economic
mistakes in history.

63
00:02:00,630 --> 00:02:02,820
At first, it seemed like it would help.

64
00:02:02,820 --> 00:02:04,860
American companies
wouldn't have to compete

65
00:02:04,860 --> 00:02:06,210
with cheap imports,

66
00:02:06,210 --> 00:02:08,760
and more products would
be made in the USA.

67
00:02:08,760 --> 00:02:10,530
But there was a big problem,

68
00:02:10,530 --> 00:02:12,270
other countries fought back.

69
00:02:12,270 --> 00:02:14,280
Nations that used to trade with the US

70
00:02:14,280 --> 00:02:16,260
started raising their own tariffs,

71
00:02:16,260 --> 00:02:18,540
making it harder for American businesses

72
00:02:18,540 --> 00:02:20,220
to sell products overseas.

73
00:02:20,220 --> 00:02:22,740
Trade slowed to an absolute crawl,

74
00:02:22,740 --> 00:02:25,950
businesses collapsed and
millions lost their jobs.

75
00:02:25,950 --> 00:02:27,780
Instead of fixing the economy,

76
00:02:27,780 --> 00:02:29,880
it helped turn a regular recession

77
00:02:29,880 --> 00:02:31,650
into the Great Depression,

78
00:02:31,650 --> 00:02:34,230
one of the worst financial crises ever.

79
00:02:34,230 --> 00:02:36,060
Fast-forward nearly a century,

80
00:02:36,060 --> 00:02:39,090
and Trump has brought
back tariffs in a big way.

81
00:02:39,090 --> 00:02:41,130
In February, 2025,

82
00:02:41,130 --> 00:02:43,320
Trump announced a 10% tariff

83
00:02:43,320 --> 00:02:45,420
on Canadian energy imports,

84
00:02:45,420 --> 00:02:49,350
and a 25% tariff on other Canadian goods.

85
00:02:49,350 --> 00:02:53,040
In retaliation, Canada
imposed a 25% tariff

86
00:02:53,040 --> 00:02:54,330
on American imports.

87
00:02:54,330 --> 00:02:58,470
Then in March, Ontario
implemented a 25% surcharge

88
00:02:58,470 --> 00:03:01,020
on electricity exports to the US,

89
00:03:01,020 --> 00:03:02,820
affecting states like New York,

90
00:03:02,820 --> 00:03:04,470
Michigan and Minnesota.

91
00:03:04,470 --> 00:03:06,150
However, in my opinion,

92
00:03:06,150 --> 00:03:07,890
this was more of a symbolic move

93
00:03:07,890 --> 00:03:10,470
that wouldn't have seriously
damaged the US economy.

94
00:03:10,470 --> 00:03:12,180
However, Trump didn't hold back,

95
00:03:12,180 --> 00:03:13,830
and instead of just brushing it off,

96
00:03:13,830 --> 00:03:16,290
he fired back by increasing tariffs

97
00:03:16,290 --> 00:03:19,680
on Canadian steel and aluminum to 50%.

98
00:03:19,680 --> 00:03:21,180
Unlike Canada's move,

99
00:03:21,180 --> 00:03:22,740
this wasn't just for show,

100
00:03:22,740 --> 00:03:25,620
it hit Canada's
manufacturing industry hard,

101
00:03:25,620 --> 00:03:27,660
while also driving up steel prices

102
00:03:27,660 --> 00:03:29,250
for American businesses

103
00:03:29,250 --> 00:03:30,690
that rely on imports.

104
00:03:30,690 --> 00:03:32,790
But why am I telling you all this?

105
00:03:32,790 --> 00:03:35,250
Well, this is where the
real problem starts.

106
00:03:35,250 --> 00:03:37,020
Tariffs sound good on paper,

107
00:03:37,020 --> 00:03:39,240
as they're meant to
punish foreign businesses,

108
00:03:39,240 --> 00:03:42,480
while encouraging more
stuff to be made in America.

109
00:03:42,480 --> 00:03:43,740
But in reality,

110
00:03:43,740 --> 00:03:45,480
they end up hurting regular people

111
00:03:45,480 --> 00:03:46,710
more than anyone else.

112
00:03:46,710 --> 00:03:47,760
As a business owner

113
00:03:47,760 --> 00:03:51,270
who manufactures products in
imports from China myself,

114
00:03:51,270 --> 00:03:53,520
I know that when businesses are forced

115
00:03:53,520 --> 00:03:55,320
to pay more for materials,

116
00:03:55,320 --> 00:03:57,330
they don't just absorb the cost,

117
00:03:57,330 --> 00:03:59,160
they pass it on to their customers.

118
00:03:59,160 --> 00:04:01,260
That means higher prices on cars,

119
00:04:01,260 --> 00:04:03,240
appliances and electronics.

120
00:04:03,240 --> 00:04:04,290
In addition to this,

121
00:04:04,290 --> 00:04:06,090
food becomes more expensive

122
00:04:06,090 --> 00:04:08,370
because supply chains get disrupted,

123
00:04:08,370 --> 00:04:10,800
meaning that everyday
essentials cost more,

124
00:04:10,800 --> 00:04:13,410
stretching household budgets even further.

125
00:04:13,410 --> 00:04:14,490
On top of that,

126
00:04:14,490 --> 00:04:16,440
other countries aren't just sitting around

127
00:04:16,440 --> 00:04:18,180
while Trump raises tariffs,

128
00:04:18,180 --> 00:04:19,680
they're forming new alliances

129
00:04:19,680 --> 00:04:21,330
to trade without the US.

130
00:04:21,330 --> 00:04:23,160
China is leading the charge

131
00:04:23,160 --> 00:04:24,690
with the BRICS Alliance,

132
00:04:24,690 --> 00:04:28,500
partnering with Brazil,
Russia, India and South Africa

133
00:04:28,500 --> 00:04:30,900
to reduce dependence on American trade.

134
00:04:30,900 --> 00:04:33,390
So the more the US isolates itself,

135
00:04:33,390 --> 00:04:36,030
the more other countries
look elsewhere for business.

136
00:04:36,030 --> 00:04:37,860
So what's my opinion on all of this

137
00:04:37,860 --> 00:04:39,540
as an experienced investor?

138
00:04:39,540 --> 00:04:42,030
Well, if Trump goes all
in on this trade war,

139
00:04:42,030 --> 00:04:45,270
history suggests it'll
do more harm than good.

140
00:04:45,270 --> 00:04:48,240
While some industries might
get a short-term boost,

141
00:04:48,240 --> 00:04:49,500
the long-term damage,

142
00:04:49,500 --> 00:04:52,650
such as higher prices, weaker global ties

143
00:04:52,650 --> 00:04:54,510
and a slowing US economy,

144
00:04:54,510 --> 00:04:56,790
could far outweigh any benefits.

145
00:04:56,790 --> 00:04:59,280
But if I'm being completely honest,

146
00:04:59,280 --> 00:05:02,010
I don't think Trump
actually wants high tariffs.

147
00:05:02,010 --> 00:05:03,690
I know that sounds crazy,

148
00:05:03,690 --> 00:05:04,680
but hear me out.

149
00:05:04,680 --> 00:05:08,550
Trump is at his core, a
businessman and a deal maker,

150
00:05:08,550 --> 00:05:09,660
just like me.

151
00:05:09,660 --> 00:05:11,940
That's why I believe he's using tariffs

152
00:05:11,940 --> 00:05:13,740
as a negotiation tactic,

153
00:05:13,740 --> 00:05:15,330
not as an end goal.

154
00:05:15,330 --> 00:05:17,130
So if that's true,

155
00:05:17,130 --> 00:05:18,540
what does he actually want?

156
00:05:18,540 --> 00:05:21,450
Well, I think he's
after free global trade,

157
00:05:21,450 --> 00:05:23,640
but on terms that favor the US.

158
00:05:23,640 --> 00:05:25,020
And if he pulls that off,

159
00:05:25,020 --> 00:05:27,090
it could pay off big time.

160
00:05:27,090 --> 00:05:28,320
However, the problem is,

161
00:05:28,320 --> 00:05:31,560
his approach is creating
massive uncertainty.

162
00:05:31,560 --> 00:05:33,150
The constant backtracking,

163
00:05:33,150 --> 00:05:35,280
new tariffs and mixed signals

164
00:05:35,280 --> 00:05:37,020
are spooking the stock market

165
00:05:37,020 --> 00:05:39,660
because investors hate unpredictability.

166
00:05:39,660 --> 00:05:41,310
If this drags on too long,

167
00:05:41,310 --> 00:05:43,410
it could shake confidence so much

168
00:05:43,410 --> 00:05:46,140
that it pushes the
economy towards recession.

169
00:05:46,140 --> 00:05:48,720
Something even Trump's own administration

170
00:05:48,720 --> 00:05:50,460
has admitted they're willing to risk.

171
00:05:50,460 --> 00:05:53,640
Right now, the market isn't
just reacting to tariffs,

172
00:05:53,640 --> 00:05:56,790
it's reacting to uncertainty
about what comes next.

173
00:05:56,790 --> 00:05:58,110
And in investing,

174
00:05:58,110 --> 00:06:01,565
uncertainty is one of the
biggest killers of confidence.

175
00:06:01,565 --> 00:06:03,690
(keys clacking)
(upbeat music)

176
00:06:03,690 --> 00:06:07,260
Trigger two is Trump's stance on NATO.

177
00:06:07,260 --> 00:06:09,990
Trump has openly questioned
the role of NATO,

178
00:06:09,990 --> 00:06:12,900
the military alliance that
protects Western countries.

179
00:06:12,900 --> 00:06:14,520
He suggested that the US

180
00:06:14,520 --> 00:06:16,290
shouldn't keep defending allies

181
00:06:16,290 --> 00:06:18,960
unless they start paying more
for their own protection.

182
00:06:18,960 --> 00:06:21,330
While that might sound like a fair demand,

183
00:06:21,330 --> 00:06:24,510
if the US steps back from
its NATO commitments,

184
00:06:24,510 --> 00:06:26,310
it could create a power vacuum

185
00:06:26,310 --> 00:06:28,980
that countries like Russia
and China might exploit.

186
00:06:28,980 --> 00:06:31,140
Markets hate uncertainty.

187
00:06:31,140 --> 00:06:34,470
The second investors sense that
world stability is at risk,

188
00:06:34,470 --> 00:06:35,303
they panic.

189
00:06:35,303 --> 00:06:36,780
If NATO weakens,

190
00:06:36,780 --> 00:06:37,980
it could encourage Russia

191
00:06:37,980 --> 00:06:39,780
to push further into Europe

192
00:06:39,780 --> 00:06:42,120
or even lead to new conflicts

193
00:06:42,120 --> 00:06:44,160
as countries try to adjust to a world

194
00:06:44,160 --> 00:06:47,220
without the USA acting as
the global police force.

195
00:06:47,220 --> 00:06:50,160
More conflicts mean
higher military spending,

196
00:06:50,160 --> 00:06:52,320
unpredictable trade relationships

197
00:06:52,320 --> 00:06:54,510
and spikes in energy prices,

198
00:06:54,510 --> 00:06:57,003
all of which can rattle the stock market.

199
00:06:57,003 --> 00:06:59,160
(keys clacking)
(upbeat music)

200
00:06:59,160 --> 00:07:02,550
Trigger three is Trump's secret plan.

201
00:07:02,550 --> 00:07:04,440
There's been a theory circulating

202
00:07:04,440 --> 00:07:07,560
that Trump may be crashing
the stock market on purpose.

203
00:07:07,560 --> 00:07:09,510
I know that sounds crazy,

204
00:07:09,510 --> 00:07:11,190
but there is some evidence for it.

205
00:07:11,190 --> 00:07:13,980
Trump has never been a fan
of high interest rates.

206
00:07:13,980 --> 00:07:16,500
In fact, he's called them ridiculous,

207
00:07:16,500 --> 00:07:18,690
and has openly attacked
the Federal Reserve

208
00:07:18,690 --> 00:07:19,740
for keeping them high.

209
00:07:19,740 --> 00:07:22,020
Now, here's where it gets interesting.

210
00:07:22,020 --> 00:07:24,240
The Fed is technically independent,

211
00:07:24,240 --> 00:07:25,920
meaning Trump can't just tell them

212
00:07:25,920 --> 00:07:27,480
to cut interest rates,

213
00:07:27,480 --> 00:07:30,990
but their decisions are
based on economic conditions.

214
00:07:30,990 --> 00:07:32,520
If the stock market crashes

215
00:07:32,520 --> 00:07:34,500
and a recession seems inevitable,

216
00:07:34,500 --> 00:07:35,940
the Fed has no choice

217
00:07:35,940 --> 00:07:38,490
but to step in and slash interest rates

218
00:07:38,490 --> 00:07:40,350
to prevent a total meltdown.

219
00:07:40,350 --> 00:07:43,140
But why does Trump want lower rates?

220
00:07:43,140 --> 00:07:45,330
Well, because high interest rates

221
00:07:45,330 --> 00:07:47,220
slow down the economy,

222
00:07:47,220 --> 00:07:49,890
businesses borrow less, stocks struggle,

223
00:07:49,890 --> 00:07:51,540
people stop spending as much,

224
00:07:51,540 --> 00:07:53,430
and for Trump, who loves growth

225
00:07:53,430 --> 00:07:56,070
and hates anything that
makes America look weak,

226
00:07:56,070 --> 00:07:56,910
they're a problem.

227
00:07:56,910 --> 00:07:59,850
It's not just about making
the stock market go up,

228
00:07:59,850 --> 00:08:01,320
it's way bigger than that.

229
00:08:01,320 --> 00:08:06,320
The US government is drowning
in $36.5 trillion of debt.

230
00:08:06,690 --> 00:08:08,370
And when interest rates are high,

231
00:08:08,370 --> 00:08:10,470
the cost of that debt
goes through the roof.

232
00:08:10,470 --> 00:08:13,380
Think of it like a
massive credit card bill.

233
00:08:13,380 --> 00:08:17,040
Imagine you owe $36,500,

234
00:08:17,040 --> 00:08:20,610
and your credit card company
charges 10% interest per year.

235
00:08:20,610 --> 00:08:22,440
That means before you even start

236
00:08:22,440 --> 00:08:24,120
paying down the actual debt,

237
00:08:24,120 --> 00:08:29,120
you're being charged
$3,650 every single year

238
00:08:29,160 --> 00:08:30,270
just in interest.

239
00:08:30,270 --> 00:08:31,950
Now, imagine the credit card company

240
00:08:31,950 --> 00:08:35,250
suddenly slashes the interest rate to 3%.

241
00:08:35,250 --> 00:08:39,480
Instead of paying $3,650 per year,

242
00:08:39,480 --> 00:08:44,370
your interest drops to
just $1,095 annually.

243
00:08:44,370 --> 00:08:49,370
That's a saving of
$2,555 every single year.

244
00:08:50,310 --> 00:08:51,540
Now you can put this money

245
00:08:51,540 --> 00:08:53,460
towards actually paying off your debt,

246
00:08:53,460 --> 00:08:56,130
instead of just keeping
up with interest payments.

247
00:08:56,130 --> 00:08:58,770
Well, that's exactly what
Trump might be doing,

248
00:08:58,770 --> 00:09:02,490
but on a $36.5 trillion scale.

249
00:09:02,490 --> 00:09:04,440
If the Fed lowers interest rates,

250
00:09:04,440 --> 00:09:06,360
the government can refinance its debt

251
00:09:06,360 --> 00:09:07,530
at a cheaper rate,

252
00:09:07,530 --> 00:09:10,260
saving billions, if not trillions,

253
00:09:10,260 --> 00:09:11,520
in interest payments.

254
00:09:11,520 --> 00:09:13,110
This wouldn't be the first time

255
00:09:13,110 --> 00:09:14,580
something like this has happened.

256
00:09:14,580 --> 00:09:17,640
If Trump can create that
opportunity on purpose,

257
00:09:17,640 --> 00:09:20,880
it could go down as one of the
smartest economic power moves

258
00:09:20,880 --> 00:09:21,713
in history.

259
00:09:21,713 --> 00:09:23,130
If this theory is true,

260
00:09:23,130 --> 00:09:25,950
we're not looking at a
long-term economic collapse,

261
00:09:25,950 --> 00:09:27,810
we're looking at a temporary shakeup

262
00:09:27,810 --> 00:09:29,490
before a massive rebound.

263
00:09:29,490 --> 00:09:30,907
So you're probably wondering,

264
00:09:30,907 --> 00:09:33,450
"How can you benefit from this crash?"

265
00:09:33,450 --> 00:09:35,040
Well, you need to understand

266
00:09:35,040 --> 00:09:36,450
that stock market crashes

267
00:09:36,450 --> 00:09:37,950
aren't rare disasters.

268
00:09:37,950 --> 00:09:40,140
They're a normal part of investing.

269
00:09:40,140 --> 00:09:42,960
Every few years, the
stock market takes a hit.

270
00:09:42,960 --> 00:09:45,157
People panic and headlines scream,

271
00:09:45,157 --> 00:09:46,500
"The end is near,"

272
00:09:46,500 --> 00:09:48,900
but history tells us a different story.

273
00:09:48,900 --> 00:09:50,640
Every crash of the US market

